g.text: Half Light: You should punch a fucking hole in it.
Half Light: The murmur in your ears recedes slowly, your breathing normalizes. That's one lucky door.
You: Run your finger across the dent.
Inland Empire: You swallow, like you swallowed the last time. Whatever bitter emotion was swimming to the surface then -- and now -- subsides. Submerges. Sinks back into you.
Perception (Hearing): Sounds like it's coming from upstairs somewhere -- you could snoop around before going up...
Door, Room #3: The door is closed.
You: "Beauty, don't abandon me in all this ugliness!"
You: "Why are you doing this? Don't do this to me..."
Kim Kitsuragi: "We should come back in the morning."
Kim Kitsuragi: "This is the police. Can we come in?"

Esprit de Corps: Somewhere not far from here the lieutenant is preparing her file. "Klaasje Amandou," he writes. You realize the detective should be here for what comes next. It could prove... *dangerous* to go in alone.
Inland Empire: "Why are you doing this? Don't do this to me, please!" Remember? Who *was* that meant for?
Door, Room #3: There is no answer.
Perception (Hearing): You hear the shower being turned on, somewhere inside.
Jump to: [Door, Room #3: "The door is closed."]
Half Light: There we go-- *fucking whore*. What a nice thing to say, Harry. Everything is A-Okay with you.
Inland Empire: White Mourning. It was mourning all along. You should've seen it coming, it was right behind her eyes...
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant gives you a quick glance.
Inland Empire: Caustic Echo. It was darkness all along. But you were young and it was summer. You just had to take a dive...
Door, Room #3: This door can only be opened with a key or from the inside.
Electrochemistry: As you hold the metal you sense the warmth left there by her hand.
Inland Empire: A tremendous loneliness comes over you. Everybody in the world is doing something without you.
Door, Room #3: The door is closed.
Door, Room #3: "Who is it?" A woman's voice answers -- muffled by the door.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Hey! What is your problem?"
Half Light: That felt good. Everyone is a whore. Now punch a hole in the door.
Door, Room #3: "Come on up -- the door is open!" She shouts: "I'm drying my hair..."
Half Light: You hear the murmur of blood in your ears. Your back slowly relaxes when you breathe out. That's one lucky door.

Shivers: In the Jamrock Quarter, The Paliseum for music, company and men... or the Door To The River, for death and synthetic opiates. Or, way in the East in Couron, in a starlit *bote de nuits* like *La Cherte*... far from here and you, shivering dog.
Inland Empire: Beauty has abandoned you in this ugliness, honcho. And then some! You cannot even remember the *name* of beauty; what beauty was...
Door, Room #3: The door is indifferent to your loneliness. The world does not care.
Pain Threshold: The words still echo in the hallway...
Inland Empire: You're just as alone as the last time. Whatever kept you company in this world -- what kept you safe -- has left your side, never to return again.
Door, Room #3: You slam your fist into the vinyl. It does not produce a hole. The door sits sturdily in the frame and your fist hurts. This was all a very good, normal thing to do.
Physical Instrument: Not to mention *great* exercise!
Door, Room #3: The door does not care.
Empathy: He doesn't like where this is going.
Door, Room #3: There is no answer -- it's nighttime, officer.
Door, Room #3: The door feels cold.
Door, Room #3: The door is closed.
Door, Room #3: The door is mute and indifferent. Your despair is a joke to it.
Volition: Don't. Everyone is a whore? What does that even mean? Breathe in and walk away.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Stop that!" The lieutenant sounds angry.
Horrific Necktie: The door probably thinks you're a has-been loser too. You feel your funny necktie becoming tighter and tighter around your neck...
Perception (Sight): There's still a dent in the vinyl -- where you punched it before.
Door, Room #3: This little depression is all you could inflict on the door.
Electrochemistry: A young woman like this is probably out partying the night away. Drink and drugs, sweet drugs are involved. Loneliness begone...
